{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17607923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17607923"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:26:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:26:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15971"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15971"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.97,0,0,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72911"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8662"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15971"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58381"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8130"},{"type":"tags","id":"10739"},{"type":"tags","id":"10779"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20743"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72911"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner after discovering she is pregnant. She expresses concern about her age and the risks to her baby.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between maternal age and congenital anomalies?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Women over 35 years have increased risk of congenital anomalies","Maternal age only affects the risk of cardiac defects","Risk of congenital anomalies peaks at age 30 years","Maternal age has no effect on congenital anomaly risk","Women under 20 years have the highest risk of anomalies"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWomen over 35 years have an increased risk of having a baby with congenital anomalies\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly chromosomal abnormalities such as Down syndrome. The risk increases exponentially with maternal age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal age only affects cardiac defects\u003C/strong\u003E - Age affects multiple types of congenital anomalies, not just cardiac defects\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERisk peaks at age 30 years\u003C/strong\u003E - The risk continues to increase beyond age 30\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal age has no effect\u003C/strong\u003E - There is a well-established relationship between advanced maternal age and congenital anomalies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWomen under 20 years have highest risk\u003C/strong\u003E - While teenage pregnancy carries some risks, the risk of chromosomal abnormalities is lowest in younger women\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrenatal screening is particularly important for women of advanced maternal age.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Advanced maternal age (\u003E35 years) increases the risk of congenital anomalies, particularly chromosomal abnormalities","The risk of Down syndrome increases exponentially with maternal age","First trimester screening is important for early detection of congenital anomalies"],"references":["Ahn D, Kim J, Kang J, Kim YH, Kim K. Congenital anomalies and maternal age: A systematic review and meta-analysis of observational studies. Acta Obstet Gynecol Scand. 2022 May;101(5):484-498. doi: 10.1111/aogs.14339. Epub 2022 Mar 14. PMID: 35288928; PMCID: PMC9564554.","Wojcik MH, Agrawal PB. Deciphering congenital anomalies for the next generation. Cold Spring Harb Mol Case Stud. 2020 Oct 7;6(5):a005504. doi: 10.1101/mcs.a005504. PMID: 32826208; PMCID: PMC7552931.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58381"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15971"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58381"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T13:44:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T15:27:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8662"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72911"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updat